Abstract classes and interfaces in Java are both used to achieve abstraction, but they serve different design purposes. While they may look similar at first glance, the way classes interact with them is fundamentally different.

The diagram above clearly illustrates this difference:

abstract_class
Depiction of Abstract class and Interface
Abstract Class
An abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated directly. It acts as a base class for other related classes and can contain both abstract and concrete methods. In the diagram, Shape is an abstract class.

abstract class Shape {

    // Abstract method
    abstract double area();

    // Concrete method
    void display() {
        System.out.println("This is a shape");
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {

    int radius = 5;

    // Implementing abstract method
    @Override
    double area() {
        return 3.14 * radius * radius;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Shape shape = new Circle();  // Upcasting
        shape.display();
        System.out.println("Area of Circle: " + shape.area());
    }
}

Output
This is a shape
Area of Circle: 78.5
Explanation:

Shape is an abstract class with an abstract method area() and a concrete method display().
Circle extends Shape and implements the area() method.
Shape shape = new Circle(); shows upcasting.
shape.display() calls the parent class method.
shape.area() executes the child class method at runtime, demonstrating polymorphism.


Interface
An interface defines a set of methods that a class must implement. It focuses on what a class can do, not how it does it. On the right side of the image, Drawable is an interface.




// Interface
interface Drawable {
    void draw();

// Interface
interface Drawable {
    void draw();
}

// Implementation class
class Rectangle implements Drawable {
    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing Rectangle");
    }
}

// Main class
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Interface reference pointing to implementation object
        Drawable d = new Rectangle();
        d.draw();
    }
}

Output
Drawing Rectangle
Explanation:

Drawable is an interface that declares the abstract method draw().
Rectangle implements the Drawable interface and provides the method implementation.
@Override ensures the method correctly overrides the interface method.
Main contains the entry point of the program.
Drawable d = new Rectangle(); demonstrates interface-based polymorphism.
d.draw(); calls the Rectangle implementation at runtime, showing dynamic binding.
